10873, "(fr)The Regulus system was colonized by a conglomerate of corporate interests which had been given an unprecedentedly generous charter by the Alliance liaison office in nearby Polaris. Notable companies including the Han-Ronald Corporation, Diamant-Eye Pharmaceuticals, and Perun Reactor Systems almost immediately moved their corporate headquarters to the new $quotebusiness-friendly$quote Regulus colonies. The Regulus charter was challenged as an illegal quid pro quo arrangement, but delays in prosecution combined with a subtle loophole allowed the charter to remain in effect. The government of Regulus, elected from among the directors of the most powerful corporations, passed an extensive series of legislation intended to attract workers to the system. War refuges, released felons, and other vulnerable people flocked to Regulus, enticed by the possibility of a fresh start. What they found was nothing short of abject exploitation.<br/><br/>In time, the people of Regulus banded together. A solidarity movement, calling itself the Regulus Workers' Syndicate after its decentralized nature, began to push back against corporate abuse. When Regulus' corporate leaders failed to provide services like security and adequate medical care, the Syndicate stepped in. When the corporations moved to suppress Syndicate activity, the Syndicate moved to protect itself. While the corporations had the advantages of better funding and the law on their side, the workers of the Syndicate had nothing to lose. When security providers began to openly support the Syndicate, Regulus' government employed underhanded tactics to suppress it. Agreeing to some of the workers' demands in exchange for carefully chosen concessions gradually eroded the Syndicate's unity and will until, eventually, corporate negotiators were able to install more $quotemoderate$quote leaders. Eventually, the Syndicate became a shadow of its former self - just another of the quasi-legal guilds operating in Regulus, although a powerful one, with much of the shipping, security, and healthcare markets under their control. Even legitimate businesses often feel the need to register with them for $quoteprotection$quote.<br/><br/>The GTA Human Rights Commission views the decay of the Regulus Syndicate - the word $quoteWorkers'$quote has long since been dropped from the name - into its current form as one of the Alliance's worst failures. Unionization, the Commission argues, has historically been a crucial tool for disadvantaged groups to stand up to power. They go on to say that the GTA need only have provided the barest support to the Workers' Syndicate, but failed to do so for fear of upsetting corporate interests. The Alliance has not refuted this statement. Operations are ongoing to weaken the Syndicate's hold over Regulus, Sirius, and Polaris. Some seek to remove particularly troublesome criminal kingpins from power, or play off different Syndicate groups against each other. Others operate more indirectly, providing employment or social services untainted by Syndicate influence. The unfortunate reality, however, is that stabilizing the situation in Regulus may require more assets than the GTA can currently provide."
10874, "(fr)The Adhara Coalition is a secessionist power centered in the Adhara system. The Coalition formed in the aftermath of the ADEIS conflict, which ended with the A.D.E.IS.01 command ship crashing into Adhara's capital planet, Annwn, while attempting to harvest material from the planet's surface settlements. The death toll of A.D.E.IS.01's attack was incalculable, as was its impact on the planet's biosphere$semicolon total ecological collapse was avoided only an emergency reconfiguration of the weather control satellites maintained by Annwn's tourist board. Public outcry was immediate, and the vote to declare independence had support from every major party in Adharan politics. The Procyon People's Party soon joined with them on ideological grounds.<br/><br/>The Adhara Coalition's military is centered around the GTD Malendroke. The Malendroke's commander, Admiral Ayda Shirazi, maintained strong ties to the Adharan populace, and was a central figure in the independence movement. The Malendroke has been joined by defectors from 6th Fleet, the GTC Remembrance and GTC Rayne out of Procyon, and private vessels from both systems, with signs of possible logistical support out of Polaris. The Coalition's breakaway has caused Epsilon Pegasi to become a battleground system, drawing the ire of local residents.<br/><br/>The Adhara Coalition's existence provides a unique threat to Alliance interests. Without reliable access to Epsilon Pegasi, the Polaris, Regulus, and Sirius systems have become isolated, requiring Allied ships to pass through the Vasudan-controlled Deneb system. This both interferes with anti-pirate operations and, more pressingly, limits access to the critical Han-Ronald shipyards. This state of affairs has given the Parliamentary Vasudan Empire considerable diplomatic leverage. In advance of possible supply issues, the Alliance has proactively put in orders for Triton Dynamics' Ulysse fighter and the LNA-designed Týr interceptor, with plans in place to reactivate older fighters if needed."
10875, "(fr)The Second Dawn Society is a paramilitary organization operating in Luyten. The SDA believes that a second Shivan Incursion is inevitable, and that a sufficiently prepared, sufficiently independent organization could provide a bastion for human survival should conventional military resistance fail, eventually bringing about a $quotesecond dawn$quote for the species. To this end, the SDA are developing a network of low-visibility Oort Cloud stations, each tasked with specific survival purposes, with enough redundancies to recover from the loss of a single station. While the SDA estimate they are roughly twenty years away from realizing their objectives, they have already established their core infrastructure, an efficient command structure, and a well-trained fighter corps. Recruitment focused on disaffected members of society, promising a new - if unconventional - life with a bigger purpose to it. The Second Dawn Society is strictly a Terran organization, owing to the difficulties in maintaining food production and medical care for two separate species in a survival situation.<br/><br/>The Second Dawn Society owes its existence to Amira Ekul, a one-time holonovel star and heir to a fortune measured in the billions. During the chaos of the Shivan attack on Riviera Station, Ekul's transport collided with another vessel, leaving it unable to initiate subspace. While Ekul survived the attack, it left them with severe neurological damage, motor impairment, and near-blindness, exacerbated by their prolonged time in a survival suit without medical attention. As the Shivan Incursion wore on, Ekul lent financial support where they could, but ultimately felt compelled to become more actively involved. When the Luyten New Alliance was granted autonomy, Ekul proposed a partnership. Their nascent organization would take up responsibility for policing the system, freeing the LNA to focus on their research. In exchange, the LNA would offer advanced technologies for the SDA stations<br/><br/>The Society's main strategy during a second Shivan Incursion would be one of stealth. Once fully operational, their stations could remain undetected in the Oort Cloud for decades. Their fighter corps' main asset, the TF Pélé, is designed to make long patrols to monitor Shivan activity. SDA strikecraft have good subspace maneuverability in spite of their large size, making them effective fast response units$semicolon should a patrol detect Shivan activity, the Society would have the option to respond with overwhelming force, destroying the target through massed railgun fire and jumping away before enemy reinforcements can arrive<br/><br/>After the Battle of Megiddo Station, the Second Dawn Society abandoned their semi-isolationist perspective to join the fight against the raiders and Hammer of Light."
10876, "(fr)[This is a translation of an article intended for Vasudan observers. A copy of the original may be requested from any terminal.]<br/><br/>The Galactic Terran Alliance is the unified Terran government, formed to provide a framework for humanity's diverse cultures to coexist. A plurality of viewpoints is at the Alliance's core. Earth's ancient cultures find new expression together among the stars$semicolon religions and philosophies dating back thousands of years debate with those founded within a human lifespan. The diversity of human cultures, ideologies, and ethnicities is a central pillar of human society even today. The Alliance formed out of a period of intense internecine conflict in the early days of human spaceflight. The Unification War left humanity bloodied and exhausted, and its aftermath came with a period of introspection. How could we ensure such a thing would never happen again? The answer was ultimately simple: together.<br/><br/>The Alliance's capital is Exarque Station in Delta Serpentis, having been moved from Sol following the destruction of the Lucifer. The collapse of the Sol jump node came unexpectedly, leaving many senior members of the Alliance government stranded$semicolon for many positions, the line of succession could not find a suitable replacement outside of Sol, triggering a round of special elections. For the time being, the size of Political diversity was unfortunately degraded during the emergency, with a coalition of the Conservative and Moderate parties opposed by the Liberal Socialists, although a growing Labor party provides a third option. The transition also brought with it hard questions about the nature of Allied government, as the historically large degree of autonomy given to Alliance systems has proven a barrier to reconstruction efforts. For the time being, the size of the Alliance's legislative body, the General Assembly, has been reduced to allow for more efficient negotiations.<br/><br/>The decentralized nature of Allied government has unfortunately allowed for illegal activity to flourish on the fringes of society, and the Alliance navy puts forth considerable effort to curtailing them. Much like the Hammer of Light, these organizations operate outside the bounds of Alliance law and prey on the vulnerable for their own ends. It is our hope that, in peacetime, both the criminal groups and the power structures that enable them may be brought to heel."
10877, "(fr)The Parliamentary Vasudan Empire was our enemy during the Fourteen Years War. Emphasis must be placed on the word $quotewas$quote. Our civilizations cooperated to drive back the Shivan Incursion, and the possibility of a lasting peace is upon us. Maintaining the cease-fire is therefore of the utmost importance. We must not allow personal feelings or the Hammer of Light to reignite old vendettas. General Order 32 was put in place for a reason, and any officer or enlisted personnel who does not believe they can abide by its requirements may request a transfer without penalty.<br/><br/>Politically, Vasudan society is structured quite unlike our own. The Emperor enjoys considerable personal power, bound more by tradition than law$semicolon however, there is considerable precedent for the courts to limit or even dethrone an unfit Emperor, with or without Parliamentary support. The Emperor's primary support in governance comes from the $quoteAmbassadors$quote, the official Imperial liaisons to different government offices. (The same word is used for ambassadors between nations, leading to an unfortunate ambiguity which translation software struggles to clarify.) While most Imperial affairs do not concern the Emperor directly, the centralization of power leads to Vasudan government being generally more cohesive than our own. Notably, while the PVE holds much less territory than the GTA, each of its systems is much more densely populated, with a much greater exploitation of natural resources. It is estimated that Alpha Centauri alone has an economic output equivalent to Delta Serpentis and Beta Aquilae together.<br/><br/>On its surface, Vasudan society appears to be much less diverse than ours$semicolon the reality is more complex. Vasudan culture is somewhat at odds with itself, with competitions between individuals, organizations, and ideologies being just as, if not more, prevalent than in Terran space. In human history, these competitions often gave way to violence. In Vasudan history, however, they are far more focused on artistic and philosophical spheres in ways that seem impossibly subtle to Terran observers. During Earth's ancient history, a conflict between nobles or nations might involve anything from economic sanctions to the deployment of armed forces. An equivalent conflict in Vasuda's history might instead center on the sale of art objects. This is not to say that Vasudan history is free of internecine fighting, as the Hammer of Light movement demonstrates, and these conflicts have an unfortunate tendency to involve governmental and legal matters. During the Fourteen Years War, it was believed that the conflict began in part due to a Terran mishandling of Vasudan language$semicolon discussions during peacetime reveal that the then-Emperor was influenced by the machinations of a traditionalist group whose members went on to hold leadership positions in the Hammer of Light. In all interactions with our Vasudan colleagues, it is crucial to remember that they developed in a radically different environment than our own, and it would be chauvinistic to expect their psychology to resemble ours. The Vasudan perspective may be difficult to understand, but it must be accepted."
10878, "(fr)The Unification War was a conflict throughout Sol and Delta Serpentis in the 22nd century. The invention of jump drives lead to vastly increased contact between Earth, Mars, and Jupiter, dragging previously buried tensions into the forefront of public consciousness$semicolon the discovery of the jump node to Delta Serpentis only inflamed them further. The dominance of corporate interests in early space flight meant that conflict between naval ships was extremely rare$semicolon instead, nations focused on commerce raiding, with massive civilian death tolls and general unrest quickly following. Many of the common elements of today's environment were first established during the early Unification War, such as the proliferation of armed cargo haulers and reliance on private security.<br/><br/>By some counts, the Unification War had as many as fourteen distinct belligerents, including planetary governments, mutual defense compacts among the Jovian system and the asteroid belt, pirate groups with no larger allegiance, and two independence movements, a short-lived one on Earth's moon and another which laid claim to Delta Serpentis. The now-well-know phenomenon of node shifts was discovered during the war, when a cruiser group out of Delta Serpentis returning to Sol found itself arriving, not in Neptunian orbit as expected, but within range of Earth's orbital artillery. In the end, human lives proved to be the most important resource. Put simply, Earth could shrug off what other powers would consider devastating defeats as $quoteacceptable losses$quote. The surrender of Mars to Earth paved the way for the war's end, but victory was not without cost. Earth's private sector economic activity had all but collapsed, and damage to the planet's biosphere rivaled the 21st-century plutocratic period$semicolon Martian terraforming had been set back almost a century by debris impacts$semicolon the Jovian government had been all but overwhelmed by pirates in converted Belt mining ships. Humanity withdrew to lick its wounds.<br/><br/>The Galactic Terran Alliance emerged from the ashes. The name was aspirational: Galactic, meaning a focus on exploration, not warfare$semicolon Terran, a new identity in rejection of those which had brought the war about$semicolon Alliance, emphasizing mutual assistance and cooperation. Each of the major powers was given a new role. Earth would be the Alliance's capital, handling administrative matters and hosting delegates from across Terran space. The seat of the Admiralty moved, fittingly, to Mars, with Martian corporations given favorable treatment in Navy contracts. Jupiter became the industrial capital, exploiting the planet's vast quantities of economically useful gases to drive a new era in orbital construction. As before, the Belt would supply raw materials, but it would do so as an equal partner with full representation in the General Assembly. As for Delta Serpentis, it would represent what it always had - a gateway to the rest of the galaxy, and the future."
10879, "(fr)To say that first contact with the Parliamentary Vasudan Empire did not go smoothly would be an understatement. The specific cause of the war was unknown at the time, but has become well-understood since the cease fire. Prior to first contact, Vasudan explorers had entered the Antarès system and flagged it as viable for colonization$semicolon however, Vasudan expansion focused on thoroughness over speed, and almost a decade passed before the Imperium returned. In the mean time, Terran colonists had set up shop. Without a common language or even reference point, representatives of both species were forced to rely on crude approximations$semicolon the Terran designation came away with the impression that Antarès was being annexed, a reasonable fear given the powerful turrets visible on the Vasudan ships, while the Vasudans believed the Terran colony was preparing to enter the nearby Vasuda system by force, a perspective reinforced by a powerful fundamentalist group with ties to the military-industrial complex.<br/><br/>The Fourteen Years War was highly asymmetric. The Vasudan focus on slow, methodical expansion gave the Vasudan navy a significant technological edge, but the Alliance navy had learned plenty of tricks from the Unification War. Old starfighters, reactivated and retrofitted with modern systems, gave the Alliance a tactical edge$semicolon the Imperium's first attempt, the Anubis fighter, was outclassed by even the ancient Terran Pie, and flown by a greenfield pilot corps with no experience to draw upon. The Imperium's advantage lay in its warships. The Alliance had operated under the assumption that the flexibility of subspace-capable strikecraft rendered heavier vessels obsolete, maintaining only a small number of gunships for fire support. The loss of entire squadrons attacking Vasudan freighters, let alone proper cruisers, showed just how mistaken this belief was. In time, both sides copied each other's technology, and the war ground on for fourteen years.<br/><br/>While intermittent cease-fires had been negotiated, none would last more than a month - until the arrival of the Shivans forced the issue. Old animosities were burned away under the threat of existential threat. It is telling that neither the emergence of the Hammer of Light nor the anti-Vasudan rhetoric of the Hades Rebellion was sufficient to reignite hostilities. Still, peace is a fragile thing, and all Allied personnel are under strict orders to maintain proper behavior in all interactions with Imperial citizens."
10880, "(fr)The Shivan Incursion began in January of 2335 with the attack on Riviera Station in Ross 128. Early combat with the Shivans revealed them to possess extremely advanced technology, including fighter-scale shields and stealth systems which made them all but impervious to conventional attack. The Galactic Terran Alliance and Parliamentary Vasudan Empire set aside their differences to combat this new threat. Early operations centered on the capture of Shivan technology to even the odds. In an unprecedented show of trust, when the Alliance's new Avenger cannon was found to be effective against shield systems, it was made available to Imperial forces - an ironic development given how hard the Alliance had worked to keep the design out of Vasudan hands.<br/><br/>The capture of Shivan shield systems allowed Allied and Imperial fighters to mount their own versions of the technology, and Shivan sensors proved effective at penetrating their stealth. Every currently active fighter and bomber in both navies includes replicas of the original Shivan components. The success, however narrow, of these early operations lead the Alliance to attempt the capture of a Shivan cruiser, the Taranis. While the Taranis was being studied at Tombaugh Station in the Ribos system, the Shivan warship Lucifer made its first appearance, destroying the station, its attending ships, and even the Taranis itself before rampaging throughout the system.<br/><br/>The Lucifer proved a particularly thorny problem due to its unique shield system. Shivan fighter shields provide very efficient protection from small arms fire, but the Lucifer's shields proved completely impenetrable to all known weapons. Every engagement with the Lucifer ended in retreat, and attempts to cut its supply lines proved ineffective. After the Battle of Deneb, the Lucifer and its battlegroup were able to enter the Vasuda system virtually unopposed.<br/><br/>The destruction of Vasuda Prime was a tragedy on a cosmic scale. Even at the darkest points of the Unification War, orbital bombardment had been regarded as beyond the pale. Even so, the battle had a silver lining. Vasudan refuges fled Shivan forces into the Altair system, where they discovered relics of a previously unknown species$semicolon a mystic among the expedition team recognized a sacred writing system from Vasudan myth and created a rough translation, lending considerable credibility to stories of alien influence on early Vasudan society. The artifacts described the destruction of an alien empire to Shivan forces, culminating in an unsuccessful last stand at their homeworld. With military victory or even long-term survival off the table, the few survivors dedicated themselves to forming a new legacy: providing technology to track the Lucifer through subspace, where shield systems do not function. Terran and Vasudan scientists alike descended on Altair to reverse-engineer the technology, giving rise to $quotesubspace tracking$quote, or SUTRAC, as a distinct field of study.<br/><br/>The discovery was just in time. As Shivan forces entered Alpha Centauri from Vasuda, their advanced sensors did what the Vasudans could not: detect signs of life in Sol. The Lucifer set course, forcing its way through multiple systems. Ultimately, the GTD Bastion tried to intercept the Lucifer at the Sol jump node, but was outmaneuvered, leading to its bomber wings pursuing the Lucifer without support. The Ancient technology did its job, and the Lucifer was brought down before it could arrive - at the cost of collapsing the Sol node itself, cutting human society in half."
10881, "(fr)Galactic Terran Intelligence expanded rapidly during the Fourteen Years War, leaving it operating largely without effective oversight. To some within the organization, this was an opportunity. One of those people was General Andreas Rybak, whose responsibilities included Internal Security. As the Fourteen Years War ground into its fourth year, Rybak came to see the Alliance as ineffectual, bloated, and in need of reform - with himself at its head, of course. Partnering with Admiral Marcus Glaive, commander of the GTD Repulse and GTI's Research &amp$semicolon Development branch, Rybak's nascent conspiracy put out feelers, discreetly reaching out to disaffected individuals while IntSec quietly looked the other way. They pursued a subtle strategy, playing on wartime fear and hatred, offering a chance to engage in $quoteunsanctioned operations$quote which would result in high Vasudan casualties at the cost of ignoring Alliance ethical guidelines. Alliance policy, they argued, was only dragging out the war and grinding away lives on both sides. Many came to agree, and with agreement came loyalty.<br/><br/>The conspiracy was centered on R&amp$semicolonD, which - somewhat counter-intuitively - not only developed new technologies, but was the first to deploy them in the field. R&amp$semicolonD's pilots and crews had extensive experience with experimental ships, and when the conspiracy began developing stealth $quoterecon$quote fighters, nothing seemed unusual. The conspiracy's inner circle, however, understood that these ships were far from scouts, and were, in fact, an effective tool to disrupt Allied operations in preparation for a military coup. The Repulse would not be able to accomplish its objectives alone, and the conspiracy used every tool at its disposal to buy time, even disrupting Shivan cleanup operations to keep loyalist GTI units occupied. Finally, their ultimate weapon revealed itself: the Hades, a massive command carrier integrating Shivan systems, of which the most alarming were replicas of the Lucifer's main guns.<br/><br/>No ship in the Allied or Imperial navy could oppose the Hades. Plans for an overwhelming assault failed against the ship's Shivan drive systems, allowing it to outmaneuver and escape its attackers through subspace. Anything less would crumple against its beam cannons. It was as if the ghost of the Lucifer had awoken, and many lives, Terran and Vasudan both, were spent trying to hold it back. It was a Vasudan ship, the PVD Hope, which finally changed the equation. Disregarding orders to withdraw for repairs, the Hope jumped in to attack the Hades. Rather than engaging conventionally, it set a collision course for the Hades' engine section. The impact destroyed the Hope and the skeleton crew on board, but left the Hades in a precarious state. It was able to withdraw to Deneb, but the strain of the intersystem jump caused its Shivan hybrid systems to give out, leaving it stranded. The Second Battle of Deneb ended with the wreck of the Hades crashing down on Deneb III. An automated system caused it to initiate reentry procedures, but most of its technology was destroyed in the crash or intentionally scuttled by the crew. In recognition of the conspiracy's targeting of Vasudan positions and civilians, the survivors were given over to the Imperium for interrogation, where they remain to this day."
